               <msContents>
                  <summary source="#TM">Seven fragments of Demotic papyri: four preserve portions
                     of a Ptolemaic Manual on Sand Divination, and three are probably from
                     documents with traces of Greek on their back.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="egy-Egyd" source="#TM">Egyptian in Demotic script</textLang>

               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <p>The papyrus of the fragments of the divination manual is very light brown
                     colour, made of strong and thick fibres. The papyrus of the divination manual is probably
                     a palimpsest, since traces of previous writing show up clearly on frg. 1.
                     These fragments also show remnants of stucco and dark-red paint which indicate
                     that they probably derive from cartonnage.</p>
                  <objectDesc form="sheet">
                     <supportDesc material="papyrus">
                        <support>papyrus</support>
                        <extent>Seven fragments of papyrus. The dimensions given are for the largest
                           and smallest fragments respectively.<dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>105</height>
                              <width>24</width>
                           </dimensions><dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>15</height>
                              <width>10</width>
                           </dimensions></extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>Written by several hands: those of the divination manual are
                        from the same scribe, while the documentary fragments are all written by
                        separate hands.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>No vignette accompanies the text on these fragments.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>


               </physDesc>
